Feature double-tap-hide — hide recording window on double-tap
===============================================================

Java reference: src/feature_double_tap_hide/DoubleTapHideListener.java

---------------------------------------------------------------
NEW FILE: smali_classes2/com/wisky/libnotewritercomponent/view/toolbar/DoubleTapHideListener.smali

Implements View.OnClickListener. Tracks `lastClickTime` via
SystemClock.uptimeMillis(); two clicks < 300ms apart → v.setVisibility(GONE).
A single click just updates the timestamp (so a stray single tap does nothing
visible).

---------------------------------------------------------------
PATCH: smali_classes2/com/wisky/libnotewritercomponent/view/toolbar/ToolbarLayout.smali

showAudioRecordLayout(): attach the listener to mBinding.llAudioRecord
immediately before making the view visible. setOnClickListener is idempotent
so re-binding on every show is fine.

  -.method public final showAudioRecordLayout()V
  -    .locals 1
  -    iget-object p0, p0, ToolbarLayout;->mBinding:...Binding;
  -    iget-object p0, p0, ...Binding;->llAudioRecord:Landroid/widget/LinearLayout;
  -    const/4 v0, 0x0
  -    invoke-virtual {p0, v0}, LinearLayout;->setVisibility(I)V
  -    return-void
  -.end method
  +.method public final showAudioRecordLayout()V
  +    .locals 2
  +    iget-object v0, p0, ToolbarLayout;->mBinding:...Binding;
  +    iget-object v0, v0, ...Binding;->llAudioRecord:Landroid/widget/LinearLayout;
  +    new-instance v1, ...DoubleTapHideListener;
  +    invoke-direct {v1}, ...DoubleTapHideListener;-><init>()V
  +    invoke-virtual {v0, v1}, LinearLayout;->setOnClickListener(...)V
  +    const/4 v1, 0x0
  +    invoke-virtual {v0, v1}, LinearLayout;->setVisibility(I)V
  +    return-void
  +.end method

Register delta: .locals 1 → .locals 2. We stop reusing p0 as a scratch register;
v0 holds the LinearLayout, v1 holds first the listener then the visibility flag.

Why here and not in <init>: ToolbarLayout.<init> is already enormous (>150
method calls). Binding in the single show-method point keeps the patch
surface tiny and localised; idempotence covers every show.

Why llAudioRecord and not the DraggableViewWrapper: DraggableViewWrapper's
onInterceptTouchEvent returns false on ACTION_DOWN and only starts
intercepting once the touch-slop threshold is crossed. Short taps therefore
reach the child LinearLayout; OnClickListener on llAudioRecord fires as
expected. Drag still works for slow/longer movements.
